'''Alice Nzomukunda''' (born 12 April 1966) is a [[Burundi]]an politician and former [[Vice-President of Burundi|Second Vice-President]] of the country, from 29 August 2005 to 5 September 2006. She is an ethnic [[Hutu]] and was a member of the [[National Council for the Defense of Democracy-Forces for the Defense of Democracy]] (CNDD-FDD).

According to the constitution, Burundi's Second Vice-President is responsible for economic and social affairs. Nzomukunda was nominated by [[Rulers and heads of state of Burundi|President]] [[Pierre Nkurunziza]] on 29 August 2005. She was endorsed by both chambers of [[Parliament of Burundi|parliament]] ([[National Assembly of Burundi|National Assembly]] – 109 votes 'for', none 'against' and 46 votes 'for', 2 'against' in the [[Senate of Burundi|Senate]]) and immediately sworn in. She is originally from the capital city of [[Bujumbura]].

On 5 September 2006, Nzomukunda resigned as Second Vice-President,<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/pays/burundi/article_depeche.asp?art_cle=PAN60026lasitnannai0 "La situation du Burundi "reste précaire", selon Kofi Annan"], Panapress (Jeuneafrique.com), 4 November 2006 {{fr icon}}.</ref><ref name=Steps>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5316690.stm "Burundi VP steps down over graft"], BBC News, 5 September 2006.</ref> citing corruption and [[human rights]] abuses by the government, as well as casting doubt on the authenticity of a coup plot which saw former [[President of Burundi|president]] [[Domitien Ndayizeye]] arrested<ref name=Steps/> a few weeks before on August 21. She was replaced as Second Vice-President by [[Marina Barapama]].

Nzomukunda subsequently became First Vice-President of the [[National Assembly of Burundi|National Assembly]].<ref name=Entame>[http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200802110206.html "Burundi: Le CNDD-FDD entame le processus de chasser Alice Nzomukunda du bureau de l'Assemblée Nationale."], ''Burundi Réalités'', Bujumbura (allAfrica.com), 10 February 2008.</ref> In January 2008, Nzomukunda was expelled from the CNDD-FDD "for internal disciplinary reasons" at an extraordinary congress of the party. The CNDD-FDD also decided to remove her from her post as First Vice-President of the National Assembly,<ref name=Main>[http://en.afrik.com/news11337.html "Burundi’s main opposition party suspends participation in parliament"], Panapress (Afrik.com), February 22, 2008.</ref> and on 8 February 2008 it was announced in the National Assembly that her post was vacant; according to [[Evariste Ndayishimiye]], the President of the CNDD-FDD Parliamentary Group, since Nzomukunda had been expelled from the CNDD-FDD, she was no longer part of its parliamentary group, "did not represent anything", and was not entitled to the post of First Vice-President of the National Assembly. Other parties in the National Assembly disputed this, however, arguing that such a decision would have to be made by the National Assembly as a whole, not by a single party.<ref name=Entame/> The [[Front for Democracy in Burundi]] (FRODEBU) suspended its participation in the National Assembly to protest the use of force against Nzomukunda. Ndayishimiye said that parliamentary affairs should not be disrupted by internal party matters and alleged that FRODEBU had secret reasons for defending Nzomukunda.<ref name=Main/>

