{{Infobox person | name = Alim Kouliev | image =Alim Kouliev.JPG | imagesize =200px | alt = | caption =''Master and Margarita''. Rehearsal | birthname = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1959|6|24}} | birth_place = [[Nalchik]], [[Kabardino-Balkar ASSR]], [[USSR]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} Death date then birth --> | death_place = | othername = | occupation = [[Stage actor]], [[film actor]], [[theater director]] | nationality = [[Balkar]] | yearsactive = | spouse = | domesticpartner = | website = }}
'''Alim Kaisynovich Kouliev''' (born June 24, 1959) is a Russian-American [[actor]], [[theatre director]] and [[screenwriter]] of [[Balkar]] origin. Kouliev was born in [[Nalchik]] — a small city in [[USSR]]. His father was the [[Balkar]] poet [[Qaysin Quli|Kaisyn Kuliev]]. His elder brother [[Eldar Kuliev]] is a [[Russians|Russian]] [[film director]] and a [[screenwriter]] ( died January 14, 2017 in [[Moscow]]). His younger brother [[Azamat Kuliev]] is the [[Russia]]n [[Painting|painter]], living and working in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]. At the age of seven, Kouliev was influenced by [[Vladimir Visotsky]] an acclaimed Russian actor, poet and singer, one of his father's younger colleagues in a poetry field. Alim decided to become an actor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alim Kouliev. Interview|url=http://www.blago-mh.ru/issues/20/29_kuliev.php|publisher=Magazine ''Мужской характер'' #20|language=Russian|accessdate=September 14, 2009}}</ref>
== Biography ==
He studied acting at the [[Russian Academy of Theatre Arts]] (GITIS) in [[Moscow]]. After serving in the [[Soviet Army]], he continued his education at the [[All-Union State Institute of Cinematography]] (VGIK) in [[Moscow]], where he graduated from the acting class of [[Yevgeny Matveyev]], an acclaimed master of theater and cinema.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yevgeny Matveyev |url=http://www.rusactors.ru/m/matveev_e/index.shtml|publisher=Rusactors.ru|language=Russian|accessdate=September 14, 2009}}</ref> His class mate was [[Natalya Vavilova]]. Kouliev also studied stage directing at GITIS in 1981.
Ever since he was a student, Kouliev appeared on professional stage. His first significant role on stage was [[Mercutio]] in [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' at [[Aleksandr Demidov]] [[Theater-Studio]], where he also plaid Atavio in ''[[The Moods of Marianne]]'' by [[Alfred de Musset]] and Meleander in [[Maurice Maeterlinck]]'s ''[[Aglavain and Selyzett]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alim Kouliev|url=http://www.kino-teatr.ru/kino/acter/m/sov/241944/bio/|publisher=Kино-театр.ру|language=Russian|accessdate=September 1, 2009}}</ref> He broke into films starring as Joseph Codrero in ''[[Copper Angel (film)|Copper Angel]]'' with [[Leonid Kuravlyov]], [[Anatoly Borisovich Kuznetsov|Anatoly Kuznetsov]], [[Aleksandr Filippenko]], [[Leonid Yarmolnik]]. He has twelve years of acting experience working in several leading Moscow theaters and has had several roles in famous Russian feature films. He has also performed extensively as an actor for radio and TV. Kouliev created many great characters in classic and contemporary productions, under the best Russian theatrical and cinema directors.
In 1991 his life changed dramatically. He moved to the [[United States]].
After the long break in his career as an actor Kouliev made his comeback. In [[Los Angeles]], he became a key member of the theatrical troupe ''Dreamhouse Ensemble'', where he played Sasha Smirnoff in ''[[Room Service (play)|Room Service]]'' and Uncle Tovit in ''Jimmy Christ''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alim Kouliev|url=http://www.dreamhousetheater.com/Welcome.html|publisher=Dreamhouse Ensemble|accessdate=August 18, 2012}}</ref> At the present time the producer-actor-director works in [[Hollywood]] with "The Master Project", his own stage adaptation of [[Mikhail Bulgakov]]’s novel ''[[The Master and Margarita]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title= The Devil World in The City of Angels|url=http://www.stihi.ru/2009/04/07/7575|publisher=Stihi.ru|language=Russian|accessdate=September 1, 2009}}</ref> The Staging of Master and Margarita has been Kouliev's long-cherished dream as a director. He vividly expresses himself in the Master Project as a mature and sophisticated painter of life.
