{{advert|date=February 2018}} {{Infobox writer | name = Josh Shipp | image = Youth-speaker-josh-shipp.jpg | caption = Josh Shipp in 2014 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|1|20|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]], [[United States]] | occupation = [[Author]], [[Motivational speaker|Youth Speaker]], TV Personality | nationality = American | subject = Youth Advocacy | movement = | period = 1999–present | influenced = | signature = | website = {{URL|joshshipp.com}} }} '''Josh Shipp''', (born January 20, 1982) is an American youth motivational speaker, best-selling author, and TV personality.<ref name="Foster Care Youth Hear From Nationally Renown Advocate">{{cite web|title=CBS Denver|url=http://denver.cbslocal.com/2016/08/26/colorado-foster-care-youth-hear-from-nationally-renown-advocate/|publisher=CBS Denver}}</ref><ref name="Bestsellers, Hardcover Nonfiction, Week of September 25, 2017">{{cite web|title=Publishers Weekly Bestseller List|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:rt1y1waXazIJ:https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/nielsen/hardcovernonfiction.html+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us|publisher=Publishers Weekly}}</ref> He is most known for his [[TED (conference)|TEDx]] talk entitled “Every Kid is One Caring Adult Away from Being a Success Story”<ref>{{cite web|title=TEDxRidderParkDriveED|url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/15294|publisher=TEDx}}</ref> and his television programs including [[Teen Trouble]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barney|first1=Chuck|title=New Lifetime show features Bay Area motivational speaker Josh Shipp|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2012/12/26/new-lifetime-show-features-bay-area-motivational-speaker-josh-shipp/|website=Mercury News|publisher=Bay Area News Group|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> which aired on [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] and [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] executive produced by Ellen Rakieten of [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ng|first1=Philiana|title=Lifetime to Launch 'Teen Trouble' Series|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/lifetimes-teen-trouble-series-390538|website=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>
Josh was president of Oklahoma [[DECA (organization)|DECA]] in high school and began speaking professional shortly thereafter at the age of 17.<ref>{{cite web|last1=WARLICK MOORE|first1=HEATHER|title=Former foster child hopes to inspire others to change their lives for the better|url=http://newsok.com/article/3613422|website=New Oklahoma|publisher=NewsOK.com|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> He has since spoken at large events such as the [[National FFA Organization|National FFA]] convention<ref>{{cite web|last1=Massengill|first1=Marlee|title=Bainbridge FFA Lands in Indiana|url=http://bainbridgega.com/news/publish/112510ffa.shtml|publisher=Bainbridge News|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> and the [[Students Against Destructive Decisions|SADD]] National Convention. Josh has been a spokesperson for National Foster Care Month,<ref>{{cite web|title=May is National Foster Care Month|url=http://www.healthiersf.org/FYS/Resources/documents/May%20is%20National%20Foster%20Care%20Month%202015.pdf|website=Healthier San Francisco|publisher=Youth Services Program for National Foster Care Month|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> wrote a teen advice column for [[Cosmogirl|CosmoGIRL!]], and appeared as a teen advice correspondent on MTV‘s [[Total Request Live]].
His recent work focuses on the impact parents, teachers, and caring adults have in the life of a child.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Grown-Up’s Guide to Teenage Humans|url=http://www.harperwave.com/book/9780062654069/The-Grown-Ups-Guide-to-Teenage-Humans-Josh-Shipp/bk/|website=Harper Wave|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>
