{{for|the Australian politician|Peter Milton (politician)}}
'''Peter Winslow Milton''' (born 1930) is a [[colorblind]] American [[artist]] who was diagnosed with [[deuteranopia]] after hearing a comment about the pink in his landscapes.<ref name=PWM>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/11/16/364092778/for-one-artist-colorblindness-opened-up-a-world-of-black-and-white|title=For One Artist, Colorblindness Opened Up A World Of Black And White|author=Angela Evancie|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref>
A creator of [[black and white]] [[etching]]s and [[engraving]]s that often display an extraordinary degree of photo-realistic detail placed in the service of a truly visionary aesthetic, his themes include [[architecture]], [[history]], [[mythology|myth]], and [[memory]], their intersections and hidden juxtapositions. His pieces often compress long periods of time into a single moment, as in "Family Reunion" and "The Train from Munich."{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}
Peter Milton received his MFA from [[Yale University]] in 1961. His work has been exhibited in most major museums in the U.S. and Europe, including the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and the [[Museum of Modern Art]], New York, the [[British Museum]] and the [[Tate Gallery]], London, and the [[Bibliothèque Nationale]], Paris. Two major book collections of his work have been published: ''The Primacy of Touch: The Drawings of Peter Milton'' (New York: Hudson Hills Press, 1993) and ''Peter Milton: Complete Prints 1960-1996'' (San Francisco: Chronicle Books, 1996).
