{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image =Sinhoni 31.jpg |birth_date = {{birth date|1902|01|24|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Nahar-Tov]], [[Russian Empire]] |Year of Aliyah = 1921 |death_date = {{Death date and age|1991|12|05|1902|01|24|df=y}} |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1949|1]] |party1 = [[Mapai]] |partyyears1 = 1949–1951 }}
'''Yehudit Simhonit''' (sometimes '''Simhoni''';<ref group=note>Her actual surname is "Simhoni"; however it was customary for Russian speakers to add a "t" ({{lang-he|"ת"}}) suffix to surnames of women</ref> {{lang-he|יהודית שמחונית}}; 24 January 1902 - 5 December 1991) was a Zionist activist and politician.
==Biography== Simhonit was born in [[Nahar-Tov]], an agricultural settlement in the [[Kherson Oblast]] of the [[Russian Empire]] (today in [[Ukraine]]), and attended an agricultural high school. In 1917 she joined the Zionist Student Youth Federation.
In 1921 she and her husband Mordechai Simhoni made [[aliyah]] to [[Mandatory Palestine]], and settled in [[Nahalal]], the newly established first [[moshav]]. In 1927 she became a member of the Union of Women Workers. She moved to kibbutz [[Tel Yosef]] in 1931, and moved again to [[Geva]] in 1943. A member of [[Mapai]], she represented the party in the fourth [[Assembly of Representatives (Mandate Palestine)|Assembly of Representatives]].
In 1949 she was [[Israeli legislative election, 1949|elected]] to the first Knesset on the Mapai list. However, she resigned from the Knesset on 5 February 1951 and was replaced by [[Herzl Berger]].<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mkindexByKnesset_eng.asp?knesset=1 Knesset Members in the First Knesset] Knesset website</ref>
She later worked as a member of the [[Histadrut]]'s co-ordinating committee and chief cultural and welfare officer of the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]]'s [[Women's Affairs advisor|Women's Corps]]. Between 1960 and 1965 she served as head of the Histadrut's International Relations Department.
In 1965 she left Mapai and was a founding member of [[David Ben-Gurion]]'s new [[Rafi (political party)|Rafi]] party, and was amongst its leadership until the party was dissolved in 1968. She died in 1991.
Her son, Major General [[Asaf Simhoni]], was killed in a plane crash at the end of the [[Sinai War]]. Her grandson, Avner Simhoni, was killed in 1968 when a mine exploded in the [[Gulf of Suez]] during the military operations in the [[War of Attrition]].<ref>{{cite web|title=סמל שמחוני, אבנר|url=http://www.izkor.gov.il/HalalKorot.aspx?id=92261|publisher=Izkor; The State of Israel, [[Ministry of Defense (Israel)|Ministry of Defense]]|accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref>
